### PART A: WebSocket Handlers (internal/web/ws/)

Files to create:
- internal/web/ws/mqtt.go       — /ws/mqtt: stream MqttQueue Tap events as JSON to client
- internal/web/ws/video.go      — /ws/video: stream VideoQueue H.264 frames as binary WebSocket messages
- internal/web/ws/pppp.go       — /ws/pppp-state: poll PPPP connection status every 2s, send JSON
- internal/web/ws/upload.go     — /ws/upload: stream FileTransferService Tap events (progress %) as JSON
- internal/web/ws/ctrl.go       — /ws/ctrl: bidirectional — light on/off, video profile, video enable/disable
- internal/web/ws/ws_test.go    — httptest-based tests for each handler

WebSocket library: github.com/gorilla/websocket (already in go.mod)

Critical for /ws/ctrl:
- Has INLINE auth (not middleware): first message from client must contain api_key
- If key missing or wrong: close connection with code 1008 (Policy Violation)
- After auth: accept {"cmd": "light", "value": "on|off"}, {"cmd": "video_profile", "value": "sd|hd|fhd"}, {"cmd": "video_enable", "value": true|false}
- Auth must use crypto/subtle.ConstantTimeCompare (no timing attacks)

All WS handlers:
- goroutine-safe read/write pump pattern (separate goroutines for read/write)
- Ping/pong keepalive (30s)
- Clean close on ctx.Done() or client disconnect
- Never block the Tap callback — use buffered channel (size 32) between Tap and write pump

